(8864223, 450, 'andreatarr', 'This is replaced by https://github.com/joomla/joomla-cms/pull/451', '2012-09-25 18:11:12'),
(8871362, 451, 'andreatarr', 'Having trouble getting this to reliably work on the second and third pages so closing this and will incorporate it in a general fix of the installation accessibility issues for 3.0.1.', '2012-09-25 21:40:52'),
(8902751, 453, 'sybrek', 'why ?', '2012-09-26 19:50:40'),
(8903878, 453, 'nonumber', 'Wasn''t DS supposed to be dropped?<br>Anyone can use the ''/'' now. And simply use DIRECTORY_SEPARATOR for the occasions you really need it.<br><br>Like sybrek: why?', '2012-09-26 20:23:11'),
(8903887, 453, 'nternetinspired', 'Does this PR re-introduce a deprecated feature??<br><br>', '2012-09-26 20:23:25'),
(8904418, 439, 'nternetinspired', '@elinw Any update on this? I have many others of a similar ilk as I have been writing my own content overrides for J3.0 to clean up the markup.<br><br>This is exactly the same issue as with the hr and dl changes you made; it''s the wrong markup for the context. It''s a real shame to see it ship like this.', '2012-09-26 20:35:07'),
(8909232, 453, 'dextercowley', 'We decided that two lines of code to possibly save a lot of heartburn was\r<br>worth it. Am I missing something, or is there more to this? What is the\r<br>downside? Thanks. Mark\r<br>\r<br>On Wed, Sep 26, 2012 at 1:23 PM, Seth Warburton <notifications@github.com>wrote:\r<br>\r<br>> Does this PR re-introduce a deprecated feature??\r<br>>\r<br>> —\r<br>> Reply to this email directly or view it on GitHub<https://github.com/joomla/joomla-cms/pull/453#issuecomment-8903887>.\r<br>>\r<br>>', '2012-09-26 22:45:27'),
(8911854, 453, 'mbabker', 'We''ve been saying for months now that the DS constant was going away with 3.0 and a lot of code hours went into removing its use from the CMS.  It''s been out of the master branch for several weeks now.  The replacement is a PHP native solution available no matter what J! version being supported; use a slash or PHP''s `DIRECTORY_SEPARATOR` constant.  Restoring something at the 11th hour like this is causing the "WTF!?" reactions, and making some folks question whether their time spent working on this was worth it with it being back.  Since it''s in the 3.0 package, the constant must be supported until 4.0, or are we going to drop it in the middle of the release cycle?', '2012-09-26 23:49:54'),
(8915082, 453, 'dextercowley', 'OK. After further discussion, we have decided to remove DS as originally\r<br>planned. This has been committed to Github and will be in the final 3.0.0\r<br>packages.\r<br>\r<br>Sorry about the confusion. The original process for deciding to remove it\r<br>was a good one, so I agree we shouldn''t "panic" at the last minute.\r<br>\r<br>Thanks. Mark\r<br>\r<br>\r<br>On Wed, Sep 26, 2012 at 4:49 PM, Michael Babker <notifications@github.com>wrote:\r<br>\r<br>> We''ve been saying for months now that the DS constant was going away with\r<br>> 3.0 and a lot of code hours went into removing its use from the CMS. It''s\r<br>> been out of the master branch for several weeks now. The replacement is a\r<br>> PHP native solution available no matter what J! version being supported;\r<br>> use a slash or PHP''s DIRECTORY_SEPARATOR constant. Restoring something at\r<br>> the 11th hour like this is causing the "WTF!?" reactions, and making some\r<br>> folks question whether their time spent working on this was worth it with\r<br>> it being back. Since it''s in the 3.0 package, the constant must be\r<br>> supported until 4.0, or are we going to drop it in the middle of the\r<br>> release cycle?\r<br>>\r<br>> —\r<br>> Reply to this email directly or view it on GitHub<https://github.com/joomla/joomla-cms/pull/453#issuecomment-8911854>.\r<br>>\r<br>>', '2012-09-27 00:52:04'),
(8923919, 453, 'dukeofgaming', 'I just love debates/drama about single characters in code, they always deliver =)', '2012-09-27 04:05:19'),
(8925160, 453, 'elkuku', 'Well I believe that one of those good thing about GitHub is that it gives us a bit more transparency about what''s going on. colored diffs and discussions - love it :)<br><br>IMHO the removed DS constant is one of those things that gives less headache to a dev when making an extension "fit" for the new Joomla! toys. Things like adding a Legacy postfix to classes hurt more..<br><br>It has also been well documented. See: [Compatibility issues in Joomla 3.0 - General changes](http://docs.joomla.org/Potential_backward_compatibility_issues_in_Joomla_3.0_and_Joomla_Platform_12.1)<br>> The DS constant has been removed. If you really need it you can use DIRECTORY_SEPARATOR instead.<br><br>[History](http://docs.joomla.org/index.php?title=Potential_backward_compatibility_issues_in_Joomla_3.0_and_Joomla_Platform_12.1&action=history) can be verified ;)<br><br>So - please don''t go back and forth.<br><br>Another +1 for not re-introducing a deprecated and removed feature.', '2012-09-27 04:31:22'),
(8932061, 453, 'Serhioromano', 'To me<br><br>```php<br>define(''DS'', DIRECTORY_SEPARATOR);<br>```<br><br>Just make my code shorter. I know that there is native PHP constant but I liked idea of `DS`. I would even add bunch of other shorts like<br><br>```php<br>define(''NL'', "\\n");<br>define(''SP'', "&nbsp;");<br>define(''BR'', "<br />");<br>```<br><br>Since sometimes you have to add concatenation just to use those symbols. <br><br>', '2012-09-27 10:30:03'),
(8939055, 456, 'infograf768', 'Fixed with eclipse. Thanks', '2012-09-27 15:03:38'),
(8940039, 453, 'nternetinspired', '"Well I believe that one of those good thing about GitHub is that it gives us a bit more transparency about what''s going on. colored diffs and discussions - love it :)"<br><br>@elkuku I could not agree more. <br><br>I truly hope that one day all such changes happen in public like this. It can only be a huge benefit to the project to involve community devs like this. It''s so much more human an experience than Joomlacode.<br><br>@dextercowley Thanks for taking community views into consideration so promptly and for reporting back here :) <br><br>@Serhioromano I''m not a coder, so the rights and wrongs of this are really lost on me. However, I am acutely aware than a helluva lot of people have spent a helluva lot of time removing DS from the CMS and from 3rd-party extensions, as it''s deprecation was what was previously (and repeatedly) communicated. A last minute (really last second) reversal, without any public discussion, or even a description, would have been very frustrating to say the least.', '2012-09-27 15:25:43'),
(8940366, 434, 'dextercowley', 'Fixed in master. Thanks!', '2012-09-27 15:35:03'),
(8944668, 274, 'littlebee88', 'administrator/modules/mod_title/mod_title.php Line 13<br><br>$title = JFactory::getApplication()->JComponentTitle;<br><br>JComponentTitle is not in class JApplication, needs to be changed to:<br><br>$title = JFactory::getApplication()->get(''JComponentTitle'');', '2012-09-27 17:31:08'),
(8953177, 441, 'garyamort', 'Came from the wrong branch.  Pull request updated with rtlTestingHack branch code.', '2012-09-27 20:37:57'),
(8953327, 439, 'sybrek', 'That''s a point i also didn''t understand, why using dl ?', '2012-09-27 20:42:01'),
(8954977, 439, 'nternetinspired', '@sybrek Agreed. I created content overrides for J3.0 yesterday and I''ve removed all dl/dt, as I don''t feel they are the correct markup to be using. <br><br>That said, they are not obviously and undeniably incorrect, as small, strong, i, etc. are.', '2012-09-27 21:11:19'),
(8955880, 439, 'sybrek', 'I wouldn''t say that using dl is totally wrong, i''m only wondering why we changed that.', '2012-09-27 21:38:55'),
(8959187, 439, 'elinw', 'There were some conflicts with other changes so the merge wasn''t clean.<br><br>Agree it''s a discussion about the dl but it is really appropriate when you have a term and a description (address 4444 Main Street) and you need the term for accessibility (so the screen reader can say what it is) but in this case i''m not happy with the way it is set up to be honest it was just a first pass at cleaning up and making it render correctly. <br><br>Can we please get comments into the issue tracker at joomlacode because that is where the decisions are made. We need to always have at least two good tests and time for Kyle to respond if he has concerns, though he looked at this and was fine with it.<br><br>I totally agree we want to get rid of the clearly wrong uses as quickly as we can. Please keep working on this, it is really useful.', '2012-09-28 00:01:21'),
(8959259, 458, 'elinw', 'With jui and LESS you can''t jut add to the template.css, you need to go through the compiling process', '2012-09-28 00:05:15'),
(8959709, 459, 'elsewares', 'Note: I went through the installation script, and everything *there* worked as expected.  Only the root file is giving me the error.', '2012-09-28 00:28:48'),
(8960067, 274, 'littlebee88', 'OK I was wrong this is not a bug and should be closed, if you are seeing this error it is because you have not defined the title properly when creating the toolbar: <br>JToolBarHelper::title(JText::_(''Your Title''), ''generic'');<br><br>And because of ordering you have to be sure to add the toolbar before the display in view.html.php:<br>$this->addToolbar();<br>parent::display($tpl);', '2012-09-28 00:49:33'),
(8965966, 458, 'Bakual', 'How does the compiling process work? I found the CSS info in the /media/less/jui/less/bootstrap-extended.less and can add it there.', '2012-09-28 06:40:14'),
(8967071, 459, 'infograf768', 'Have you tested on 3.0 stable?', '2012-09-28 07:48:31'),
(8967870, 439, 'nternetinspired', 'Thanks @elinw <br><br>Actually, I believe that <footer is the correct element to use for article info, and I have already implemented that in my own overrides. There''s already been quite some discussion around this, if you are interested: https://github.com/semantic-joomla/joomla-cms/commit/3f60f71b7356a4c3ed473c5dfdb04f6d2d2be88b<br><br>Actually, I''d prefer to keep comments, and discussion here for a number of reasons. It''s far more transparent and encourages community participation instead of removing discussion from the public eye. In Joomlacode it isn''t possible to comment against code, or even review it, let alone edit it. And there are no proper notifications?? WTF? It seems like a system designed to keep outsiders out. I don''t believe decisions should be made in the darkness that is Joomlacode.<br><br>We have a wonderful tool here with Github, let''s use it and keep the code, the discussion and the decisions in one place. It''s easy and fast to test right here, there''s plenty of other projects proving that.<br><br>I''m well aware that the official word is that Github does not fit the ''established process'', it''s my view that the established process is wrong. It has to be. If it makes it difficult to contribute, it''s wrong.', '2012-09-28 08:35:45'),
(8984924, 458, 'Bakual', 'Closed in favor for https://github.com/joomla/joomla-cms/pull/461 (change in LESS file)', '2012-09-28 17:37:28'),
(9001948, 460, 'infograf768', 'Fixed with Eclipse. Thanks.', '2012-09-29 08:26:46'),
(9063894, 466, 'infograf768', 'Thanks. Fixed with eclpise', '2012-10-02 09:13:37'),
(9065336, 212, 'klah', 'Is there any news on whether this will be included in a future Joomla version?\r<br>\r<br>Also (to me) the menu item management option doesn''t seem to be working. I set the permissions of a menu item for Manager to Denied for all the actions. But a manager can still happily open, edit and save the item. He can even change his own permissions.', '2012-10-02 09:35:45'),
